1. Ganapathi homam manual was created first. The ma=
ntras given for prana pratishtha of Ganapathi were taken from a reference t=
hat was dedicated to various sadhanas of Ganapathi, including different sty=
les of homam. The specific nyasa given in it is usually tied to any sadhana=
 involving the Mahaganapathi mantra. Ganaka is the rishi, Nichchrid Gayatri=
 is the metre and so on, for THAT Mahaganapathi mantra. However, that refer=
ence used the same for prana pratishtha of Ganapathi and I followed the sam=
e.
=C2=A0
Later, as I created more manuals, I switched to what we use in tr=
adition for a generic prana pratishtha of any deity in an idol or kalasha o=
r fire. Here, irrespective of the deity involved, "asunI te" is considered =
as the main mantra for invocation of divine energy.

=C2=A0
In the generic =
"asya shrI prANa pratiShThApana mantrasya" given in various manuals, one ca=
n insert the name of the deity also.
=C2=A0
Using common sense, please note=
 that it may be possible to invoke the presence of a deity in an object (fi=
re or water or idol) using a generic mantra such as "asunI te" or even a sp=
ecific mantra of that deity itself. In the end, rituals, mantras and steps =
are aids for the mind to focus on a specific form of energy and try to fill=
 itself with it. If that happens, that energy will invariably express aroun=
d one. I suggest not worrying too much about the specifics and doing what y=
our heart feels attracted to. For example, skipping whatever is given in ma=
nual and simply reading Laghu Nyasa (or any Shiva mantra you are attracted =
to) while mentally imagining that Shiva's energy is expanding in that place=
 may be more effective for one than to stick to the manual. Manual is just =
ONE template. In fact, even whatever methods have come down to us in tradit=
ion are simply templates.
=C2=A0
If She so wishes, some more clean up and r=
e-organization may happen with the manuals to make them simpler, more consi=
stent and generic.
=C2=A0
2. As for chhandas, "R^igyajussAmAtharvANi" means=
 the 4 Vedas. The 4 Vedas are mentioned as the metre of some mantras in tra=
dition to emphasize the need for understanding Self. Without a decent under=
standing and appreciation of Self, we cannot invoke any divine energy anywh=
ere.

=C2=A0
3. To make things simpler, the water offering step was not ret=
ained in all later manuals. However, it is an orthogonal step that can be a=
dded to Shiva homam also.
=C2=A0
4. If you call the "associates" after homa=
m to a deity, it is obviously understood that you are referring to the asso=
ciates of that deity. To make it generic (and make it easy to cut & paste a=
nd create multiple manuals), the name was not included as it is not absolut=
ely necessary. If you prefer, you can add it.
